contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Basis of 
presentation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company&amp;#146;s 
financial statements have&#13;been prepared in accordance with accounting 
principles generally accepted in the United States of America (&amp;#147;U.S. 
GAAP&amp;#148;).The&#13;preparation of financial statements in conformity with 
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of 
America&#13;requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect 
the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure&#13;of contingent 
assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported 
amounts of revenues and expenses&#13;during the reporting period. Actual results
could differ from those estimates.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Management further acknowledges
that it is&#13;solely responsible for adopting sound accounting practices, 
establishing and maintaining a system of internal accounting control&#13;and
preventing and detecting fraud. The Company's system of internal accounting 
control is designed to assure, among other items,&#13;that 1) recorded 
transactions are valid; 2) valid transactions are recorded; and 3) transactions 
are recorded in the proper period&#13;in a timely manner to produce financial 
statements which present fairly the financial condition, results of operations 
and cash&#13;flows of the Company for the respective periods being 
presented.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Use of 
Estimates&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The preparation of financial 
statements in&#13;conformity with generally accepted accounting principles 
requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect 
reported&#13;amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent 
assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statement and&#13;the 
reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Actual 
results could differ from the estimates.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent:
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cash and Cash
Equivalent&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;For financial statement 
presentation purposes,&#13;the Company considers those short-term, highly liquid
investments with original maturities of three months or less to be cash 
or&#13;cash equivalents.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Property and 
Equipment&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;New property and equipment are 
recorded at&#13;cost. Property and equipment included in the bankruptcy 
proceedings and transferred to the Trustee had been valued at 
liquidation&#13;value. Depreciation is computed using the straight-line method 
over the estimated useful lives of the assets, generally 5 
years.&#13;Expenditures for renewals and betterments are capitalized. 
Expenditures for minor items, repairs and maintenance are charged 
to&#13;operations as incurred. Gain or loss upon sale or retirement due to 
obsolescence is reflected in the operating results in the period&#13;the event 
takes place.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Valuation of 
Long-Lived Asset&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;We review the recoverability of
our long-lived&#13;assets including equipment, goodwill and other intangible 
assets, when events or changes in circumstances occur that indicate that&#13;the
carrying value of the asset may not be recoverable. The assessment of possible 
impairment is based on our ability to recover&#13;the carrying value of the 
asset from the expected future pre-tax cash flows (undiscounted and without 
interest charges) of the&#13;related operations. If these cash flows are less 
than the carrying value of such asset, an impairment loss is recognized for 
the&#13;difference between estimated fair value and carrying value. Our primary 
measure of fair value is based on discounted cash flows.&#13;The measurement of 
impairment requires management to make estimates of these cash flows related to 
long-lived assets, as well as&#13;other fair value
determinations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Stock Based 
Compensation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Stock-based awards are 
accounted for using&#13;the fair value method in accordance with ASC 718, 
&lt;i&gt;Share-Based Payments&lt;/i&gt;. Our primary type of share-based 
compensation consists&#13;of stock options. We use the Black-Scholes option 
pricing model in valuing options. The inputs for the valuation analysis of 
the&#13;options include the market value of the Company&amp;#146;s common stock,
the estimated volatility of the Company&amp;#146;s common stock,&#13;the 
exercise price of the warrants and the risk free interest 
rate.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Accounting 
For Obligations And Instruments&#13;Potentially To Be Settled In The 
Company&amp;#146;s Own Stock&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&#13;We account for obligations and instruments 
potentially to be settled in the Company&amp;#146;s stock in accordance with 
FASB ASC 815,&#13;&lt;i&gt;Accounting for Derivative Financial Instruments. 
&lt;/i&gt;This issue addresses the initial balance sheet classification and 
measurement&#13;of contracts that are indexed to, and potentially settled in, 
the Company&amp;#146;s own stock.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Fair value of
financial instruments&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent:
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company follows paragraph 
825-10-50-10&#13;of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for disclosures 
about fair value of its financial instruments and paragraph 820-10-35-37&#13;of 
the FASB Accounting Standards Codification (&amp;#147;Paragraph 820-10-35-
37&amp;#148;) to measure the fair value of its financial&#13;instruments. 
Paragraph 820-10-35-37 establishes a framework for measuring fair value in 
accounting principles generally accepted&#13;in the United States of America 
(U.S. GAAP), and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. To increase 
consistency and&#13;comparability in fair value measurements and related 
disclosures, Paragraph 820-10-35-37 establishes a fair value hierarchy 
which&#13;prioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair 
value into three (3) broad levels. The fair value hierarchy&#13;gives the 
highest priority
 to quoted prices (unadjusted) in active markets for identical assets or 
liabilities and the lowest priority&#13;to unobservable inputs. The three (3) 
levels of fair value hierarchy defined by Paragraph 820-10-35-37 are described 
below:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Level 1: Quoted market prices 
available in&#13;active markets for identical assets or liabilities as of the 
reporting date.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Level 2: Pricing inputs other 
than quoted prices&#13;in active markets included in Level 1, which are either 
directly or indirectly observable as of the reporting 
date.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Level 3: Pricing inputs that 
are generally&#13;observable inputs and not corroborated by market 
data.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The carrying amount of the 
Company&amp;#146;s&#13;financial assets and liabilities, such as cash, prepaid 
expenses and accrued expenses approximate their fair value because of 
the&#13;short maturity of those instruments. The Company&amp;#146;s notes 
payable approximate the fair value of such instruments based 
upon&#13;management&amp;#146;s best estimate of interest rates that would be 
available to the Company for similar financial arrangements at&#13;July 31, 
2013.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company does not have any 
assets or liabilities&#13;measured at fair value on a recurring or a non-
recurring basis.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Earnings per 
Common Share&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;We compute net income (loss) 
per share in accordance&#13;with ASC 260, &lt;i&gt;Earning per Share&lt;/i&gt;. 
ASC 260 requires presentation of both basic and diluted earnings per share (EPS)
on the&#13;face of the income statement. Basic EPS is computed by dividing net 
income (loss) available to common shareholders (numerator)&#13;by the weighted 
average number of shares outstanding (denominator) during the period. Diluted 
EPS gives effect to all dilutive&#13;potential common shares outstanding during 
the period using the treasury stock method and convertible preferred stock using
the&#13;if-converted method. In computing Diluted EPS, the average stock price 
for the period is used in determining the number of shares&#13;assumed to be 
purchased from the exercise of stock options or warrants. Diluted EPS excludes 
all dilutive potential shares if their&#13;effect is anti dilutive. All per 
share disclosures retroactively reflect shares outstanding or issuable as though
the reverse split&#13;had occurred as of January 31, 
2010.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Income 
taxes&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company follows Section 
740-10-30 of the&#13;FASB Accounting Standards Codification, which requires 
recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected 
future&#13;tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial 
statements or tax returns. Under this method, deferred tax&#13;assets and 
liabilities are based on the differences between the financial statement and tax
bases of assets and liabilities using&#13;enacted tax rates in effect for the 
fiscal year in which the differences are expected to reverse. Deferred tax 
assets are reduced&#13;by a valuation allowance to the extent management 
concludes it is more likely than not that the assets will not be realized. 
Deferred&#13;tax assets and liabilities are measured using enacted tax rates 
expected to apply to taxable income in the fiscal years in which&#13;those 
temporary differences are expected to be recovered or settled. The effect on 
deferred tax assets and liabilities of a change&#13;in tax rates is recognized 
in the Statements of Income and Comprehensive Income in the period that includes
the enactment date.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company adopted section 
740-10-25 of the&#13;FASB Accounting Standards Codification (&amp;#147;Section 
740-10-25&amp;#148;) with regards to uncertainty income taxes. Section 740-10-
25&#13;addresses the determination of whether tax benefits claimed or expected 
to be claimed on a tax return should be recorded in the&#13;financial 
statements. Under Section 740-10-25, the Company may recognize the tax benefit 
from an uncertain tax position only if&#13;it is more likely than not that the 
tax position will be sustained on examination by the taxing authorities, based 
on the technical&#13;merits of the position. The tax benefits recognized in the 
financial statements from such a position should be measured based on&#13;the 
largest benefit that has a greater than fifty percent (50%) likelihood of being 
realized upon ultimate settlement. Section&#13;740-10-25 also provides guidance 
on de-recognition, classification, interest and penalties on income taxes, 
accounting in interim&#13;periods and requires increased disclosures. The 
Company had no material adjustments to its liabilities for unrecognized 
income&#13;tax benefits according to the provisions of Section 740-10-
25.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Uncertain Tax
Positions&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Financial Accounting 
Standards Board issued&#13;Interpretation No. 48, &amp;#147;Accounting for 
Uncertainty in Income Taxes &amp;#150; an interpretation of FASB Statement No. 
109, Accounting&#13;for Income Taxes&amp;#148; (&amp;#147;FIN No. 48&amp;#148;) 
which was effective for the Company on February 1, 2007. FIN No. 48 
addresses&#13;the determination of whether tax benefits claimed or expected to 
be claimed on a tax return should be recorded in the financial&#13;statements. 
Under FIN No. 48, the Company may recognize the tax benefit from an uncertain 
tax position only if it is more likely&#13;than not that the tax position will 
be sustained on examination by the taxing authorities based on the technical 
merits of the&#13;position. The tax benefits recognized in the financial 
statements from such position should be measured based on the largest 
benefit&#13;that has a greater than fifty percent likelihood of being realized 
upon ultimate settlement. FIN No. 48 also provides guidance&#13;on 
derecognition, classification, interest and penalties, accounting in interim 
periods and disclosure requirements.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Our federal and state income 
tax returns&#13;are open for fiscal years ending on or after January 31, 2007. 
We are not under examination by any jurisdiction for any tax&#13;year. At  July 
31, 2013 we had no material unrecognized tax benefits and no adjustments to 
liabilities or operations were&#13;required under FIN 
48.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cash flows 
reporting&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
 style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;The Company adopted paragraph 230-10-45-24&#13;of the FASB 
Accounting Standards Codification for cash flows reporting, classifies cash 
receipts and payments according to whether&#13;they stem from operating, 
investing, or financing activities and provides definitions of each category, 
and uses the indirect or&#13;reconciliation method (&amp;#147;Indirect 
method&amp;#148;) as defined by paragraph 230-10-45-25 of the FASB Accounting 
Standards Codification&#13;to report net cash flow from operating activities by 
adjusting net income to reconcile it to net cash flow from operating 
activities&#13;by removing the effects of (a) all deferrals of past operating 
cash receipts and payments and all accruals of expected future
operating&#13;cash receipts and payments and (b) all items that are included in 
net income that do not affect operating cash receipts and payments.&#13;The 
Company reports the reporting currency equivalent of foreign currency cash 
flows, using the current exchange rate at the time&#13;of the cash flows and the
effect of exchange rate changes on cash held in foreign currencies is reported 
as a separate item in&#13;the reconciliation of beginning and ending balances of
cash and cash equivalents and separately provides information about 
investing&#13;and financing activities not resulting in cash receipts or 
payments in the period pursuant to paragraph 830-230-45-1 of the 
FASB&#13;Accounting Standards Codification.&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify;
text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;u&gt;Subsequent 
events&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company follows the 
guidance in Section&#13;855-10-50 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification 
for the disclosure of subsequent events. The Company will evaluate 
subsequent&#13;events through the date when the financial statements were 
issued. Pursuant to ASU 2010-09 of the FASB Accounting Standards 
Codification,&#13;the Company as an SEC filer considers its financial statements
issued when they are widely distributed to users, such as through&#13;filing 
them on EDGAR.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Recent Accounting 
Pronouncements&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In October 2012, the Financial 
Accounting Standards&#13;Board (FASB) issued Accounting Standards Update (ASU) 
2012-04, ''Technical Corrections and Improvements&amp;#34; in Accounting 
Standards&#13;Update No. 2012-04. The amendments in this update cover a wide 
range of Topics in the Accounting Standards Codification. These&#13;amendments 
include technical corrections and improvements to the Accounting Standards 
Codification and conforming amendments related&#13;to fair value measurements. 
The amendments in this update will be effective for fiscal periods beginning 
after December 15, 2012.&#13;The adoption of ASU 2012-04 is not expected to have
a material impact on our financial position or results of 
operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In August 2012, the FASB issued
ASU 2012-03,&#13;&amp;#34;Technical Amendments and Corrections to SEC Sections: 
Amendments to SEC Paragraphs Pursuant to SEC Staff Accounting Bulletin&#13;(SAB)
No. 114, Technical Amendments Pursuant to SEC Release No. 33-9250, and 
Corrections Related to FASB Accounting Standards Update&#13;2010-22 (SEC 
Update)&amp;#34; in Accounting Standards Update No. 2012-03. This update amends 
various SEC paragraphs pursuant to the&#13;issuance of SAB No. 114. The adoption
of ASU 2012-03 is not expected to have a material impact on our financial 
position or results&#13;of operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent:
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In July 2012, the FASB issued 
ASU 2012-02,&#13;&amp;#34;Intangibles -Goodwill and Other (Topic 350): Testing 
Indefinite-Lived Intangible Assets for Impairment&amp;#34; in 
Accounting&#13;Standards Update No. 2012-02. This update amends ASU 2011-08, 
Intangibles -Goodwill and Other (Topic 350): Testing Indefinite-
Lived&#13;Intangible Assets for Impairment and permits an entity first to assess
qualitative factors to determine whether it is more likely&#13;than not that an 
indefinite-lived intangible asset is impaired as a basis for determining whether
it is necessary to perform the&#13;quantitative impairment test in accordance
with Subtopic 350-30, Intangibles -Goodwill and Other -General Intangibles Other
than&#13;Goodwill. The amendments are effective for annual and interim 
impairment tests performed for fiscal years beginning after September&#13;15, 
2012. Early adoption is permitted, including for annual and interim impairment 
tests performed as of a date before July 27,&#13;2012, if a public entity's 
financial statements for the most recent annual or interim period have not yet 
been issued or, for nonpublic&#13;entities, have not yet been made available for
issuance. The adoption of ASU 2012-02 is not expected to have a material 
impact&#13;on our financial position or results of 
operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In September 2011 Accounting 
Standards Update&#13;No. 2011-08, Intangibles - Goodwill and Other (Topic 350): 
Testing Goodwill for impairment. This ASU's objective is to simplify&#13;the 
process of performing impairment testing for Goodwill. With this update a 
company is allowed to asses qualitative factors,&#13;first, to determine if it 
is more likely than not (greater than 50%) that the FV is less than the carrying
amount. This would be&#13;done, prior to performing the two-step goodwill 
impairment testing, as prescribed by Topic 350. Prior to this ASU, all 
entities&#13;were required to test, annually, their good will for impairment by 
Step 1 - comparing the FV to the carrying amount, and if impaired,&#13;then step
2 - calculate and recognize the impairment. Therefore, the fair value 
measurement is not required, until the &amp;#34;more&#13;likely than 
not&amp;#34; reasonableness test is concluded. Effective for annual and interim 
goodwill impairment tests performed for&#13;fiscal years beginning after 
December 15, 2011.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In May 2011, FASB issued 
Accounting Standards&#13;Update No. 2011-04, Fair Value Measurement (Topic 820):
&lt;i&gt;Amendments to Achieve Common Fair Value Measurement and Disclosure 
Requirements&#13;in U.S. GAAP and IFRSs &lt;/i&gt;. This ASU clarifies the 
board's intent of current guidance, modifies and changes certain guidance 
and&#13;principles, and adds additional disclosure requirements concerning the 3
levels of fair value measurements. Specific amendments&#13;are applied to FASB 
ASC 820-10-35, Subsequent Measurement and FASB ASC 820-10-50, Disclosures. This 
ASU is effective for interim&#13;and annual periods beginning after December 15,
2011.&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In June 2011, FASB issued 
Accounting Standards&#13;Update No. 2011-05, Comprehensive Income (Topic 220): 
&lt;i&gt;Presentation of Comprehensive Income &lt;/i&gt;. - ASU 2011-05. Current
US GAAP&#13;allows companies to present the components of comprehensive income 
as a part of the statement of changes in stockholders' equity.&#13;This ASU 
eliminates that option. in this Update, an entity has the option to present the 
total of comprehensive income, the components&#13;of net income, and the 
components of other comprehensive income either in a single continuous statement
of comprehensive income&#13;or in two separate but consecutive statements. In 
both choices, an entity is required to present each component of net income 
along&#13;with total net income, each component of other comprehensive income 
along with a total for other comprehensive income, and a total&#13;amount for 
comprehensive income This ASU is effective interim and annual periods beginning 
after December 15, 2011. This ASU should&#13;be applied retrospectively. There 
are no specific transition disclosures&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent:
 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company has 
implemented all new accounting&#13;pronouncements that are in effect. These 
pronouncements did not have any material impact on the financial statements 
unless otherwise&#13;disclosed, and the Company does not believe that there are 
any other new accounting pronouncements that have been issued that 
might&#13;have a material impact on its financial position or results of
operations.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:BasisOfPresentationAndSignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:IncomeTaxDisclosureTextBlock contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-
31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-
align: justify"&gt;Deferred taxes are provided on a liability&#13;method whereby
deferred tax assets are recognized for deductible temporary differences and 
operating loss and tax credit carry&#13;forwards and deferred tax liabilities 
are recognized for taxable temporary differences. Temporary differences are the 
differences&#13;between the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and their
tax bases. Deferred tax assets are reduced by a valuation allowance&#13;when, in
the opinion of management, it is more likely than not that some portion or all 
of the deferred tax assets will not be&#13;realized. Deferred tax assets and 
liabilities are adjusted for the effects of changes in tax laws and rates on the
date of enactment.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Net deferred tax assets consist
of the following&#13;components as of January 31, 2013.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p

text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;At January 31,
2013, the Company had net operating&#13;loss carry forwards of approximately 
$163,319 that may be offset against future taxable income from the year 2013 to 
2033. No tax&#13;benefit has been reported in the January 31, 2013 financial 
statements since the potential tax benefit is offset by a 
valuation&#13;allowance of the same amount.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify;
text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Due to the 
change in ownership provisions of&#13;the Tax Reform Act of 1986, net operating 
loss carry forwards for Federal Income tax reporting purposes are subject to 
annual limitations.&#13;Should a change in ownership occur, net operating loss 
carry forwards may be limited as to use in future years.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:IncomeTaxDisclosureTextBlock>

0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In June and again in October of
2011&lt;b&gt; &lt;/b&gt;we&#13;declared a reverse split of our common 
stock.&lt;b&gt; &lt;/b&gt;The combined result of the reverse splits was that 
that every twenty thousand&#13;(20,000) issued and outstanding shares of common 
stock of the Corporation were automatically converted into 1 share of common 
stock.&#13;Any resulting share ownership interest of fractional shares was 
rounded up to the first whole integer in such a manner that all&#13;rounding was
done to the next single share. Except as otherwise noted, all share, option and 
warrant numbers have been restated&#13;to give retroactive effect to these 
reverse splits. All per share disclosures retroactively reflect shares
outstanding or issuable&#13;as though the reverse split had occurred January 31,
2010.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;

gaap:OrganizationConsolidationBasisOfPresentationBusinessDescriptionAndAccountin

10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The

with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America 
(&amp;#147;U.S. GAAP&amp;#148;).The&#13;preparation of financial statements in 
conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of
America&#13;requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect 
the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure&#13;of contingent 
assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported 
amounts of revenues and expenses&#13;during the reporting period. Actual results
could differ from those estimates.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt

0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,

that it is&#13;solely responsible for adopting sound accounting practices, 
establishing and maintaining a system of internal accounting control&#13;and 
preventing and detecting fraud. The Company's system of internal accounting 
control is designed to assure, among other items,&#13;that 1) recorded 
transactions are valid; 2) valid transactions are recorded; and 3) transactions 
are recorded in the proper period&#13;in a timely manner to produce financial 
statements which present fairly the financial condition, results of operations 
and cash&#13;flows of the Company for the respective periods being 
presented.&lt;/p&gt;</us-

    <us-gaap:PropertyPlantAndEquipmentPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2013-02-
01to2013-07-31">&lt;p style="margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;font 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;New property and equipment 
are&#13;recorded at cost. Property and equipment included in the bankruptcy 
proceedings and transferred to the Trustee had been valued&#13;at liquidation 
value. Depreciation is computed using the straight-line method over the 
estimated useful lives of the assets, generally&#13;5 years. Expenditures for 
renewals and betterments are capitalized. Expenditures for minor items, repairs 
and maintenance are&#13;charged to operations as incurred. Gain or loss upon
sale or retirement due to obsolescence is reflected in the operating 
results&#13;in the period the event takes place.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:PropertyPlantAndEquipmentPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:ImpairmentOrDisposalOfLongLivedAssetsPolicyTextBlock 
contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;We review the recoverability of
our long-lived&#13;assets including equipment, goodwill and other intangible 
assets, when events or changes in circumstances occur that indicate that&#13;the
carrying value of the asset may not be recoverable. The assessment of possible 
impairment is based on our ability to recover&#13;the carrying value of the 
asset from the expected future pre-tax cash flows (undiscounted and without 
interest charges) of the&#13;related operations. If these cash flows are less 
than the carrying value of such asset, an impairment loss is recognized for 
the&#13;difference between estimated fair value and carrying value. Our primary 
measure of fair value is based on discounted cash flows.&#13;The measurement of 
impairment requires management to make estimates of these cash flows related to 
long-lived assets, as well as&#13;other fair value 
determinations.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ImpairmentOrDisposalOfLongLivedAssetsPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:ShareBasedCompensationOptionAndIncentivePlansPolicy 
contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Stock-based awards are 
accounted for using&#13;the fair value method in accordance with ASC 718, 
&lt;i&gt;Share-Based Payments&lt;/i&gt;. Our primary type of share-based 
compensation consists&#13;of stock options. We use the Black-Scholes option 
pricing model in valuing options. The inputs for the valuation analysis of 
the&#13;options include the market value of the Company&amp;#146;s common stock,
the estimated volatility of the Company&amp;#146;s common stock,&#13;the 
exercise price of the warrants and the risk free interest rate.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:ShareBasedCompensationOptionAndIncentivePlansPolicy>

tockPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-31">&lt;p style="font:

    <us-gaap:FairValueOfFinancialInstrumentsPolicy contextRef="From2013-02-
01to2013-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 
0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company follows paragraph 825-10-50-10&#13;of the
FASB Accounting Standards Codification for disclosures about fair value of its 
financial instruments and paragraph 820-10-35-37&#13;of the FASB Accounting 
Standards Codification (&amp;#147;Paragraph 820-10-35-37&amp;#148;) to measure 
the fair value of its financial&#13;instruments. Paragraph 820-10-35-37 
establishes a framework for measuring fair value in accounting principles 
generally accepted&#13;in the United States of America (U.S. GAAP), and expands 
disclosures about fair value measurements. To increase consistency 
and&#13;comparability in fair value measurements and related disclosures, 
Paragraph 820-10-35-37 establishes a fair value hierarchy which&#13;prioritizes 
the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value into three (3) 
broad levels. The fair value hierarchy&#13;gives the highest priority to quoted 
prices (unadjusted) in active markets for identical assets or liabilities and 
the lowest priority&#13;to unobservable inputs. The three (3) levels of fair 
value hierarchy defined by Paragraph 820-10-35-37 are described 
below:&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Level 1: Quoted market prices 
available in&#13;active markets for identical assets or liabilities as of the
reporting date.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Level 2: Pricing inputs other 
than quoted prices&#13;in active markets included in Level 1, which are either 
directly or indirectly observable as of the reporting 
date.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;Level 3: Pricing inputs that 
are generally&#13;observable inputs and not corroborated by market 
data.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The carrying amount of the 
Company&amp;#146;s&#13;financial assets and liabilities, such as cash, prepaid 
expenses and accrued expenses approximate their fair value because of 
the&#13;short maturity of those instruments. The Company&amp;#146;s notes 
payable approximate the fair value of such instruments based 
upon&#13;management&amp;#146;s best estimate of interest rates that would be 
available to the Company for similar financial arrangements at&#13;July 31, 
2013.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; 
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company does not have any 
assets or liabilities&#13;measured at fair value on a recurring or a non-
recurring basis.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:FairValueOfFinancialInstrumentsPolicy>
    <us-gaap:EarningsPerSharePolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-
07-31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-
align: justify"&gt;We compute net income (loss) per share in accordance&#13;with
ASC 260, &lt;i&gt;Earning per Share&lt;/i&gt;. ASC 260 requires presentation of 
both basic and diluted earnings per share (EPS) on the&#13;face of the income 
statement. Basic EPS is computed by dividing net income (loss) available to 
common shareholders (numerator)&#13;by the weighted average number of shares 
outstanding (denominator) during the period. Diluted EPS gives effect to all 
dilutive&#13;potential common shares outstanding during the period using the 
treasury stock method and convertible preferred stock using the&#13;if-converted
method. In computing Diluted EPS, the average stock price for the period is used
in determining the number of shares&#13;assumed to be purchased from the 
exercise of stock options or warrants. Diluted EPS excludes all dilutive 
potential shares if their&#13;effect is anti dilutive. All per share disclosures
retroactively reflect shares outstanding or issuable as though the reverse 
split&#13;had occurred as of January 31, 2010.&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:EarningsPerSharePolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:IncomeTaxPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-
31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-
align: justify"&gt;The Company follows Section 740-10-30 of the&#13;FASB 
Accounting Standards Codification, which requires recognition of deferred tax 
assets and liabilities for the expected future&#13;tax consequences of events 
that have been included in the financial statements or tax returns. Under this 
method, deferred tax&#13;assets and liabilities are based on the differences 
between the financial statement and tax bases of assets and liabilities 
using&#13;enacted tax rates in effect for the fiscal year in which the 
differences are expected to reverse. Deferred tax assets are reduced&#13;by a 
valuation allowance to the extent management concludes it is more likely than 
not that the assets will not be realized. Deferred&#13;tax assets and 
liabilities are measured using enacted tax rates expected to apply to taxable 
income in the fiscal years in which&#13;those temporary differences are expected
to be recovered or settled. The effect on deferred tax assets and liabilities of
a change&#13;in tax rates is recognized in the Statements of Income and 
Comprehensive Income in the period that includes the enactment 
date.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif;
margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 0.5in"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="margin: 0; 
text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The Company adopted section 740-10-25&#13;of the FASB Accounting 
Standards Codification (&amp;#147;Section 740-10-25&amp;#148;) with regards to 
uncertainty income taxes. Section&#13;740-10-25 addresses the determination of 
whether tax benefits claimed or expected to be claimed on a tax return should be
recorded&#13;in the financial statements. Under Section 740-10-25, the Company 
may recognize the tax benefit from an uncertain tax position&#13;only if it is 
more likely than not that the tax position will be sustained on examination by 
the taxing authorities, based on&#13;the technical merits of the position. The 
tax benefits recognized in the financial statements from such a position should 
be measured&#13;based on the largest benefit that has a greater than fifty 
percent (50%) likelihood of being realized upon ultimate settlement.&#13;Section
740-10-25 also provides guidance on de-recognition, classification, interest and
penalties on income taxes, accounting&#13;in interim periods and requires 
increased disclosures. The Company had no material adjustments to its 
liabilities for unrecognized&#13;income tax benefits according to the provisions
of Section 740-10-25.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:IncomeTaxPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:IncomeTaxUncertaintiesPolicy contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-
31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-
align: justify"&gt;The Financial Accounting Standards Board 
issued&#13;Interpretation No. 48, &amp;#147;Accounting for Uncertainty in Income
Taxes &amp;#150; an interpretation of FASB Statement No. 109, Accounting&#13;for
Income Taxes&amp;#148; (&amp;#147;FIN No. 48&amp;#148;) which was effective for 
the Company on February 1, 2007. FIN No. 48 addresses&#13;the determination of 
whether tax benefits claimed or expected to be claimed on a tax return should be
recorded in the financial&#13;statements. Under FIN No. 48, the Company may 
recognize the tax benefit from an uncertain tax position only if it is more 
likely&#13;than not that the tax position will be sustained on examination by 
the taxing authorities based on the technical merits of the&#13;position. The 
tax benefits recognized in the financial statements from such position should be
measured based on the largest benefit&#13;that has a greater than fifty percent 
likelihood of being realized upon ultimate settlement. FIN No. 48 also provides 
guidance&#13;on derecognition, classification, interest and penalties, 
accounting in interim periods and disclosure 
requirements.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times,
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;Our 
federal and state&#13;income tax returns are open for fiscal years ending on or 
after January 31, 2007. We are not under examination by any&#13;jurisdiction for
any tax year. At  July 31, 2013 we had no material unrecognized tax benefits and
no adjustments to&#13;liabilities or operations were required under FIN 
48.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:IncomeTaxUncertaintiesPolicy>
    <AMOG:CashFlowsReportingPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-
31">&lt;p style="margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;The Company adopted paragraph&#13;230-10-45-24
of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for cash flows reporting, 
classifies cash receipts and payments according&#13;to whether they stem from 
operating, investing, or financing activities and provides definitions of each 
category, and uses the&#13;indirect or reconciliation method (&amp;#147;Indirect
method&amp;#148;) as defined by paragraph 230-10-45-25 of the FASB 
Accounting&#13;Standards Codification to report net cash flow from operating 
activities by adjusting net income to reconcile it to net cash flow&#13;from 
operating activities by removing the effects of (a) all deferrals of past 
operating cash receipts and payments and all accruals&#13;of expected future 
operating cash receipts and payments and (b) all items that are included in net 
income that do not affect operating&#13;cash receipts and payments. The Company 
reports the reporting currency equivalent of foreign currency cash flows, using 
the current&#13;exchange rate at the time of the cash flows and the effect of 
exchange rate changes on cash held in foreign currencies is reported&#13;as a 
separate item in the reconciliation of beginning and ending balances of cash and
cash equivalents and separately provides&#13;information about investing and 
financing activities not resulting in cash receipts or payments in the period 
pursuant to paragraph&#13;830-230-45-1 of the FASB Accounting Standards 
Codification.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</AMOG:CashFlowsReportingPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:SubsequentEventsPolicyPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2013-02-

guidance&#13;in Section 855-10-50 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification 
for the disclosure of subsequent events. The Company will 
evaluate&#13;subsequent events through the date when the financial statements 
were issued. Pursuant to ASU 2010-09 of the FASB Accounting 
Standards&#13;Codification, the Company as an SEC filer considers its financial 
statements issued when they are widely distributed to users,&#13;such as through
filing them on EDGAR.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:SubsequentEventsPolicyPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:NewAccountingPronouncementsPolicyPolicyTextBlock 
contextRef="From2013-02-01to2013-07-31">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In October 2012, the Financial 
Accounting Standards&#13;Board (FASB) issued Accounting Standards Update (ASU) 
2012-04, ''Technical Corrections and Improvements&amp;#34; in Accounting 
Standards&#13;Update No. 2012-04. The amendments in this update cover a wide 
range of Topics in the Accounting Standards Codification. These&#13;amendments 
include technical corrections and improvements to the Accounting Standards 
Codification and conforming amendments related&#13;to fair value measurements. 
The amendments in this update will be effective for fiscal periods beginning 
after December 15, 2012.&#13;The adoption of ASU 2012-04 is not expected to have
a material impact on our financial position or results of 
operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In August 2012, the FASB issued
ASU 2012-03,&#13;&amp;#34;Technical Amendments and Corrections to SEC Sections: 
Amendments to SEC Paragraphs Pursuant to SEC Staff Accounting Bulletin&#13;(SAB)
No. 114, Technical Amendments Pursuant to SEC Release No. 33-9250, and 
Corrections Related to FASB Accounting Standards Update&#13;2010-22 (SEC 
Update)&amp;#34; in Accounting Standards Update No. 2012-03. This update amends 
various SEC paragraphs pursuant to the&#13;issuance of SAB No. 114. The adoption
of ASU 2012-03 is not expected to have a material impact on our financial 
position or results&#13;of operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent:
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In July 2012, the FASB issued 
ASU 2012-02,&#13;&amp;#34;Intangibles -Goodwill and Other (Topic 350): Testing 
Indefinite-Lived Intangible Assets for Impairment&amp;#34; in 
Accounting&#13;Standards Update No. 2012-02. This update amends ASU 2011-08, 
Intangibles -Goodwill and Other (Topic 350): Testing Indefinite-
Lived&#13;Intangible Assets for Impairment and permits an entity first to assess
qualitative factors to determine whether it is more likely&#13;than not that an 
indefinite-lived intangible asset is impaired as a basis for determining whether
it is necessary to perform the&#13;quantitative impairment test in accordance 
with Subtopic 350-30, Intangibles -Goodwill and Other -General Intangibles Other
than&#13;Goodwill. The amendments are effective for annual and interim 
impairment tests performed for fiscal years beginning after September&#13;15, 
2012. Early adoption is permitted, including for annual and interim impairment 
tests performed as of a date before July 27,&#13;2012, if a public entity's 
financial statements for the most recent annual or interim period have not yet 
been issued or, for nonpublic&#13;entities, have not yet been made available for
issuance. The adoption of ASU 2012-02 is not expected to have a material 
impact&#13;on our financial position or results of 
operations.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In September 2011 Accounting 
Standards Update&#13;No. 2011-08, Intangibles - Goodwill and Other (Topic 350):
Testing Goodwill for impairment. This ASU's objective is to simplify&#13;the 
process of performing impairment testing for Goodwill. With this update a 
company is allowed to asses qualitative factors,&#13;first, to determine if it 
is more likely than not (greater than 50%) that the FV is less than the carrying
amount. This would be&#13;done, prior to performing the two-step goodwill 
impairment testing, as prescribed by Topic 350. Prior to this ASU, all 
entities&#13;were required to test, annually, their good will for impairment by 
Step 1 - comparing the FV to the carrying amount, and if impaired,&#13;then step
2 - calculate and recognize the impairment. Therefore, the fair value 
measurement is not required, until the &amp;#34;more&#13;likely than 
not&amp;#34; reasonableness test is concluded. Effective for annual and interim 
goodwill impairment tests performed for&#13;fiscal years beginning after 
December 15, 2011.&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In May 2011, FASB issued 
Accounting Standards&#13;Update No. 2011-04, Fair Value Measurement (Topic 820):
&lt;i&gt;Amendments to Achieve Common Fair Value Measurement and Disclosure 
Requirements&#13;in U.S. GAAP and IFRSs &lt;/i&gt;. This ASU clarifies the 
board's intent of current guidance, modifies and changes certain guidance 
and&#13;principles, and adds additional disclosure requirements concerning the 3
levels of fair value measurements. Specific amendments&#13;are applied to FASB 
ASC 820-10-35, Subsequent Measurement and FASB ASC 820-10-50, Disclosures. This 
ASU is effective for interim&#13;and annual periods beginning after December 15,
2011.&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent: 
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;In June 2011, FASB issued 
Accounting Standards&#13;Update No. 2011-05, Comprehensive Income (Topic 220): 
&lt;i&gt;Presentation of Comprehensive Income &lt;/i&gt;. - ASU 2011-05. Current
US GAAP&#13;allows companies to present the components of comprehensive income 
as a part of the statement of changes in stockholders' equity.&#13;This ASU 
eliminates that option. in this Update, an entity has the option to present the 
total of comprehensive income, the components&#13;of net income, and the 
components of other comprehensive income either in a single continuous statement
of comprehensive income&#13;or in two separate but consecutive statements. In 
both choices, an entity is required to present each component of net income 
along&#13;with total net income, each component of other comprehensive income 
along with a total for other comprehensive income, and a total&#13;amount for 
comprehensive income This ASU is effective interim and annual periods beginning 
after December 15, 2011. This ASU should&#13;be applied retrospectively. There 
are no specific transition disclosures&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify; text-indent:
0.5in"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;The Company has implemented all
new accounting&#13;pronouncements that are in effect. These pronouncements did 
not have any material impact on the financial statements unless 
otherwise&#13;disclosed, and the Company does not believe that there are any 
other new accounting pronouncements that have been issued that might&#13;have a 
material impact on its financial position or results of 
operations.&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:NewAccountingPronouncementsPolicyPolicyTextBlock>

</LabelSeparator><Level>2</Level><ElementName>us-
gaap_BasisOfPresentationAndSignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock</ElementName><
